ents <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":8,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":43,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Valoignes was born in 1216, in Suffolk, England, his father, Thomas I de Valoignes - Lord of Hickley, was 22 and his mother, Isabel Creke, was 8. He married Rohesia Blount before 1224. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 6 August 1282, in Thetford St Mary the Less, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1216–aft 6 Aug 1282":"1216–pärast 6. augustit 1282","1216–1282":"1216–1282","1207–1271":"1207–1271","1225–1282":"1225–1282","1194–1228":"1194–1228","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","before 1224":"enne 1224","aft 6 Aug 1282":"pärast 6. augustit 1282","1271":"1271","1282":"1282","1194":"1194","Abt 1218":"umbes 1218","1228":"1228","1216":"121